## Why Performer+STRING Converges Faster

**1. Learnable Positional Encoding**

Unlike ViT and Performer which use fixed absolute positional embeddings (a lookup table), STRING uses learnable relative positional encodings. The STRING parameters are updated during training, allowing the model to adapt its positional representation to the data more effectively.

**2. Translational Invariance**

STRING provides exact translational invariance: the same object appearing at different locations in an image receives consistent positional information. Absolute positional encodings in ViT and Performer lack this property, requiring more epochs to implicitly learn positional relationships.

**3. Relative Position Information**

Relative positional encodings capture the relationship between patches (e.g. "patch A is 3 positions away from patch B"), which is more semantically meaningful for image classification than absolute positions. This allows STRING to learn useful representations more efficiently.

**Note:** Our implementation shows poor performance at epoch 1 (val_acc=19.19%) due to random initialization of STRING parameters. The model recovers quickly by epoch 3 (val_acc=91.64%), consistent with Schenck et al. (2025) who report that STRING converges faster than baseline methods once training stabilizes.

